1
00:00:32,833 --> 00:00:36,333
[KAMIJO] I am without a doubt
a seriously unlucky person.

2
00:00:36,416 --> 00:00:37,791
[blop]

3
00:00:37,875 --> 00:00:39,833
[KAMIJO] For example, let's
look back over the events

4
00:00:39,916 --> 00:00:42,791
following the Daihasei Festival.

5
00:00:42,875 --> 00:00:45,083
Things started out
badly enough, but they only

6
00:00:45,166 --> 00:00:47,666
seemed to get worse
as time went on.

7
00:00:47,750 --> 00:00:49,250
I accidentally walked
in on my teacher

8
00:00:49,333 --> 00:00:51,125
changing her clothes.

9
00:00:51,208 --> 00:00:53,458
Received a solid hair
yank from Fukiyose,

10
00:00:53,541 --> 00:00:55,666
now fully recovered.

11
00:00:55,750 --> 00:00:58,000
Was hit with a surprisingly
accurate gumball,

12
00:00:58,083 --> 00:01:00,875
launched at me by Himegami.

13
00:01:00,958 --> 00:01:02,916
And was forced to do
some weird kind of dance

14
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:05,166
around a bonfire with Misaka.

15
00:01:05,250 --> 00:01:06,833
Which lead to a kick
in the back of the head

16
00:01:06,916 --> 00:01:08,916
from her friend Kuroko.

17
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:11,458
Needless to say, I am
now bruised, beaten,

18
00:01:11,541 --> 00:01:14,416
and utterly exhausted.

19
00:01:14,500 --> 00:01:18,208
As I said before, I am
one seriously unlucky gu--

20
00:01:19,333 --> 00:01:21,708
[LADY] Congratulations!
We held a special raffle

21
00:01:21,791 --> 00:01:23,833
on the final day of
the Daihasei Festival,

22
00:01:23,916 --> 00:01:27,291
and the number you picked took
the grand prize, you lucky boy!

23
00:01:27,375 --> 00:01:29,875
And your prize is a
thrilling seven day,

24
00:01:29,958 --> 00:01:32,291
six night trip
to Northern Italy!

25
00:01:32,375 --> 00:01:35,416
[cheering and clapping]

26
00:01:35,500 --> 00:01:38,458
Huh? I really
won a trip to Italy?

27
00:01:39,083 --> 00:01:49,041
♪ [Opening Song] ♪

28
00:03:10,916 --> 00:03:12,833
[KAMIJO] I know I sound
like a broken record,


29
00:03:12,916 --> 00:03:15,541
but I am an unlucky person.


30
00:03:15,625 --> 00:03:16,958
[KAMIJO] Do I have a passport?

31
00:03:17,041 --> 00:03:20,125
Hm? I don't know.
What's a passport?

32
00:03:20,208 --> 00:03:22,750
[chuckles] I knew
something would go wrong.

33
00:03:22,833 --> 00:03:25,333
I knew this trip was
too good to be true.

34
00:03:25,416 --> 00:03:27,416
There're only two
days left 'til I leave.

35
00:03:27,500 --> 00:03:30,500
Even if I requested a
passport today, it wouldn't--

36
00:03:36,375 --> 00:03:39,000
[KAMIJO] Well, what
do you know! My passport!

37
00:03:39,083 --> 00:03:40,333
Let's take a look.

38
00:03:40,416 --> 00:03:42,583
I wonder how many foreign
countries I've been to.

39
00:03:42,666 --> 00:03:43,958
[INDEX] Oh, hey, you know what?

40
00:03:44,041 --> 00:03:46,125
I've got a little book
that looks a lot like that!

41
00:03:46,208 --> 00:03:47,583
Hm?

42
00:03:51,250 --> 00:03:52,958
What? All these
pages are blank.

43
00:03:53,041 --> 00:03:54,750
There isn't a
single stamp in this!

44
00:03:54,833 --> 00:03:56,041
Hm?

45
00:03:56,125 --> 00:03:57,208
Well, I'm confused.

46
00:03:57,291 --> 00:03:59,250
How'd you get here
with a blank passport?

47
00:03:59,333 --> 00:04:00,500
Does it really matter?

48
00:04:00,583 --> 00:04:02,291
The important thing
is that I have one.

49
00:04:02,375 --> 00:04:04,791
And since I do, can I come
along with you on your trip?

50
00:04:04,875 --> 00:04:06,958
You wouldn't leave me
here all alone, would you?

51
00:04:07,041 --> 00:04:09,583
Ah... Well, um.

52
00:04:09,666 --> 00:04:11,416
[KAMIJO] There's no reason
not to invite her, right?

53
00:04:11,500 --> 00:04:13,666
I mean, what could go wrong?

54
00:04:15,791 --> 00:04:17,375
[KAMIJO] Haven't forgotten
anything, have you?

55
00:04:17,458 --> 00:04:19,291
Your wallet, passport,
and plane ticket,

56
00:04:19,375 --> 00:04:21,958
your necessary documents, your
toothbrush and toothpaste.

57
00:04:22,041 --> 00:04:23,166
Uh, what else is there?

58
00:04:23,250 --> 00:04:24,916
Why are you being such
a worrywart about this?

59
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:27,500
I thought vacations were
supposed to be relaxing.

60
00:04:27,583 --> 00:04:29,458
Yeah. You know
what, you're right.

61
00:04:29,541 --> 00:04:32,208
I should try to calm down
and just enjoy the ride.

62
00:04:32,291 --> 00:04:33,750
That's exactly
what I'm gonna do!

63
00:04:33,833 --> 00:04:36,625
Relish the moment!
Italy, here I come!

64
00:04:36,708 --> 00:04:39,125
I hope you're ready
for Toma Kamijo!

65
00:04:39,208 --> 00:04:40,250
Yeah!

66
00:04:40,333 --> 00:04:41,583
[beep]

67
00:04:41,666 --> 00:04:44,000
[footsteps]

68
00:04:45,208 --> 00:04:47,041
[KAMIJO] Um, is there
a problem, ma'am?

69
00:04:47,125 --> 00:04:48,541
Yes, I'm afraid there is.

70
00:04:48,625 --> 00:04:49,875
[KAMIJO] Huh?

71
00:04:51,083 --> 00:04:52,500
[KAMIJO] Damn!
We have to hurry, Index!

72
00:04:52,583 --> 00:04:53,666
You need something
to wear that's not

73
00:04:53,750 --> 00:04:55,583
held together with
pieces of sharp metal!

74
00:04:55,666 --> 00:04:57,250
What? You're taking
me shopping, Toma?

75
00:04:57,333 --> 00:04:59,583
Aww, that's so sweet of you!

76
00:04:59,666 --> 00:05:01,958
[KAMIJO] All the shops are
more than a kilometer away.

77
00:05:02,041 --> 00:05:04,625
And there are only twenty-eight
minutes 'til takeoff!

78
00:05:04,708 --> 00:05:08,291
Damn, damn, damn! Damn my
stupid, awful, rotten luck!

79
00:05:08,375 --> 00:05:13,291
[aircraft noise]

80
00:05:13,375 --> 00:05:20,166
[birds chirping]

81
00:05:20,250 --> 00:05:22,583
[KAMIJO] Wow, we sure
are close to the sea, huh?

82
00:05:22,666 --> 00:05:24,125
We're surrounded by the sea.

83
00:05:24,208 --> 00:05:26,458
That's probably a more
accurate way to put it.

84
00:05:26,541 --> 00:05:28,291
To be more specific,
the town of Chioggia,

85
00:05:28,375 --> 00:05:30,958
where we currently are, is
on an island in the Adriatic.

86
00:05:31,041 --> 00:05:32,625
Yeah?

87
00:05:32,708 --> 00:05:42,666
♪

88
00:05:44,583 --> 00:05:45,666
[KAMIJO] Whew!

89
00:05:45,750 --> 00:05:46,875
You know how
after we landed,

90
00:05:46,958 --> 00:05:48,791
we spent so long running
around, looking for

91
00:05:48,875 --> 00:05:51,291
giant safety pins that our
tour guide left us behind?

92
00:05:51,375 --> 00:05:53,833
I admit, at that point I
was really starting to worry,

93
00:05:53,916 --> 00:05:55,583
but we made it
here after all.

94
00:05:55,666 --> 00:05:56,708
Well, you wouldn't
need a guide

95
00:05:56,791 --> 00:05:57,916
if you spoke the language.

96
00:05:58,000 --> 00:05:59,958
One should be at least
trilingual in a modern,

97
00:06:00,041 --> 00:06:02,375
international
society like ours.

98
00:06:02,458 --> 00:06:03,791
I don't want to be
lectured by someone

99
00:06:03,875 --> 00:06:05,750
who can't even make it
through airport security.

100
00:06:05,833 --> 00:06:07,208
Ahh!

101
00:06:14,125 --> 00:06:16,625
We can eat after we drop
off our luggage at the hotel.

102
00:06:16,708 --> 00:06:18,083
I know that!
I'm not stupid.

103
00:06:18,166 --> 00:06:20,208
But you can't blame
a girl for looking!

104
00:06:22,041 --> 00:06:23,583
[INDEX] Is that
authentic squid ink gelato?

105
00:06:23,666 --> 00:06:25,291
The food looks great.
We'll totally get some,

106
00:06:25,375 --> 00:06:26,666
but once we're all
checked in, I think that

107
00:06:26,750 --> 00:06:28,250
we should head into Venice.

108
00:06:28,333 --> 00:06:30,666
I've always wanted to ride
in a gondola, you know?

109
00:06:30,750 --> 00:06:32,416
[chuckles]

110
00:06:32,500 --> 00:06:35,333
Uh. Where'd she go?

111
00:06:35,416 --> 00:06:38,833
Hey! Index, where are you?

112
00:06:38,916 --> 00:06:41,083
C'mon this isn't funny!

113
00:06:41,166 --> 00:06:44,666
[KAMIJO] Index!
Are you out there?

114
00:06:45,500 --> 00:06:47,500
I should be careful,
or else I'm the one

115
00:06:47,583 --> 00:06:48,791
who's gonna get lost.

116
00:06:48,875 --> 00:06:51,875
[ITALIAN LADY] Ciao!
Hai qualche problema?

117
00:06:51,958 --> 00:06:53,000
Sorry?

118
00:06:53,083 --> 00:06:56,208
Ah, non sai
parlare Italiano. Eh?

119
00:06:56,291 --> 00:06:58,083
[ITALIAN LADY]
C' e un ristorante la e il

120
00:06:58,166 --> 00:07:00,083
direttore e giapponese.

121
00:07:00,166 --> 00:07:02,583
"Hola, me llamo--"
No, that isn't it.

122
00:07:02,666 --> 00:07:04,458
[nervous laughter]

123
00:07:04,541 --> 00:07:06,458
[ORSOLA] Scusi.

124
00:07:06,541 --> 00:07:08,125
Lui è un mio amico.

125
00:07:08,208 --> 00:07:11,583
La ringrazio per
la sua gentilezza.

126
00:07:11,666 --> 00:07:14,291
[ITALIAN LADY]
Hm. Prego. Ciao!

127
00:07:16,791 --> 00:07:19,750
[ORSOLA] I'm sorry. Maybe I
shouldn't have interrupted you.

128
00:07:19,833 --> 00:07:22,291
You seemed lost. I thought
you could use some help,

129
00:07:22,375 --> 00:07:24,583
but you probably had it
under control, didn't you?

130
00:07:24,666 --> 00:07:26,916
[KAMIJO] Um, Orsola?

131
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:28,458
Hi there!

132
00:07:29,958 --> 00:07:32,458
[ORSOLA] I didn't expect to
see you. What brings you here?

133
00:07:32,541 --> 00:07:36,208
[KAMIJO] Oh. I kind of won
a trip to Italy in a raffle.

134
00:07:36,291 --> 00:07:38,458
So, uh, what are you doing here?

135
00:07:38,541 --> 00:07:40,250
I thought you were in London.

136
00:07:40,333 --> 00:07:42,916
[ORSOLA] I still kept a
residence here under my name.

137
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:44,750
I'm moving out of it now.

138
00:07:44,833 --> 00:07:47,166
As I'm sure you can imagine,
things were a bit hectic

139
00:07:47,250 --> 00:07:48,708
when I switched
my allegiance from

140
00:07:48,791 --> 00:07:51,625
the Roman Orthodox to
the English Puritan Church.

141
00:07:51,708 --> 00:07:52,958
I have quite a few
things that still

142
00:07:53,041 --> 00:07:55,500
need to be moved.
But fortunately for me,

143
00:07:55,583 --> 00:07:57,708
some of the Amakusa
offered to help out.

144
00:07:57,791 --> 00:07:59,750
Isn't that kind of them?

145
00:07:59,833 --> 00:08:01,000
[KAMIJO] Wait,
when you say "Amakusa"

146
00:08:01,083 --> 00:08:03,000
do you mean the Amakusa?

147
00:08:04,083 --> 00:08:05,541
[ORSOLA] So, anyway,
what is it you were

148
00:08:05,625 --> 00:08:07,166
doing back there?
Some shopping?

149
00:08:07,250 --> 00:08:09,375
[KAMIJO] Huh?
Oh, no, that's not it.

150
00:08:09,458 --> 00:08:12,458
I brought Index with me,
and everything was going fine,

151
00:08:12,541 --> 00:08:14,250
and then she just disappeared.

152
00:08:14,333 --> 00:08:15,666
[ORSOLA] I'm starting
to think we were fated

153
00:08:15,750 --> 00:08:17,375
to run into each other!

154
00:08:17,458 --> 00:08:19,958
I mean it. This couldn't
have been better timing!

155
00:08:20,041 --> 00:08:21,375
Maybe I can
even talk you into

156
00:08:21,458 --> 00:08:22,708
helping us move my things?

157
00:08:22,791 --> 00:08:24,833
[KAMIJO] Uh.
Well, it's like I said,

158
00:08:24,916 --> 00:08:26,916
Index disappeared
and I need to find her.

159
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:30,208
[ORSOLA] Oh. That should
be easy enough to do.

160
00:08:30,291 --> 00:08:31,375
Huh?

161
00:08:31,458 --> 00:08:33,750
[INDEX] Toma! Toma!
Toma! Look at this!

162
00:08:33,833 --> 00:08:36,625
I got a discount because
I bought the economy size!

163
00:08:36,708 --> 00:08:40,250
Can you believe it? All
of this gelato, just for me!

164
00:08:41,541 --> 00:08:42,875
Yum!

165
00:08:42,958 --> 00:08:44,333
[KAMIJO] Ugh...

166
00:08:44,416 --> 00:08:47,291
There, you see. I ran into
her a little while ago too.

167
00:08:47,375 --> 00:08:50,416
She was pressed up against
the window of a gelato shop.

168
00:08:50,500 --> 00:08:52,583
So I asked a friend of
mine to invite her here.

169
00:08:52,666 --> 00:08:54,291
I thought she would be
much safer if she wasn't

170
00:08:54,375 --> 00:08:56,083
on her own in
a strange place.

171
00:08:56,166 --> 00:08:58,875
Why, Index?
Why must you do this to me?

172
00:08:58,958 --> 00:09:01,125
[INDEX] Ah, Orsola!
Will lunch be ready soon?

173
00:09:01,208 --> 00:09:02,416
Ah!

174
00:09:02,500 --> 00:09:04,250
[ORSOLA] Yes. It shouldn't
be much longer now.

175
00:09:04,333 --> 00:09:06,291
[INDEX] Hooray!

176
00:09:06,375 --> 00:09:07,916
[KAMIJO] Just my luck.

177
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:09,541
[MALE AMAKUSA 14A] That's the
guy that His Holiness holds

178
00:09:09,625 --> 00:09:12,041
in such high
esteem? Look at him.

179
00:09:12,125 --> 00:09:13,833
How powerful can he really be?

180
00:09:13,916 --> 00:09:15,208
You're only asking
that because you weren't

181
00:09:15,291 --> 00:09:17,416
with us when we helped
rescue Sister Orsola.

182
00:09:17,500 --> 00:09:18,750
If you were there,
then you would know.

183
00:09:18,833 --> 00:09:21,083
That guy pitted himself
against the Roman Orthodox

184
00:09:21,166 --> 00:09:23,291
Warrior Sisters when he
was unarmed and alone.

185
00:09:23,375 --> 00:09:25,708
Do you suppose you'd have the
guts to do something like that?

186
00:09:25,791 --> 00:09:26,958
I don't think so.

187
00:09:27,041 --> 00:09:28,375
You wanna know what's
even more impressive?

188
00:09:28,458 --> 00:09:30,291
He saw the Priestess
without her clothes on,

189
00:09:30,375 --> 00:09:32,250
and he didn't need to
be hospitalized after she

190
00:09:32,333 --> 00:09:35,625
beat him with the scabbard of
her Shichiten Shichito sword.

191
00:09:36,458 --> 00:09:38,083
[ALL] That guy's a freak.

192
00:09:38,166 --> 00:09:41,708
[KAMIJO] I can't tell. Was that
supposed to be a compliment?

193
00:09:43,166 --> 00:09:46,708
[INDEX and KAMIJO]
Wow! It looks great!

194
00:09:46,791 --> 00:09:47,958
We don't deserve this.

195
00:09:48,041 --> 00:09:49,583
We haven't even
helped you move yet.

196
00:09:49,666 --> 00:09:51,500
You shouldn't have
gone to all this trouble.

197
00:09:51,583 --> 00:09:53,625
Please, I would offer
you two my hospitality

198
00:09:53,708 --> 00:09:55,875
whether you helped or not.

199
00:09:55,958 --> 00:09:58,083
In that case, thank you!

200
00:10:02,250 --> 00:10:04,166
Care for a hot towel?

201
00:10:07,333 --> 00:10:08,250
I appreciate it.

202
00:10:08,333 --> 00:10:10,291
Oh, no problem.

203
00:10:12,416 --> 00:10:13,333
[FEMALE AMAKUSA 14A]
Well, Itsuwa?

204
00:10:13,416 --> 00:10:15,291
How did operation Hot Towel go?

205
00:10:15,375 --> 00:10:16,458
[MALE AMAKUSA 14A]
Don't be stupid.

206
00:10:16,541 --> 00:10:18,166
It's too soon
to see any results.

207
00:10:18,250 --> 00:10:19,875
We need to let things
run their course.

208
00:10:19,958 --> 00:10:21,083
[FEMALE AMAKUSA 14B] Isn't
there a more direct way

209
00:10:21,166 --> 00:10:22,250
to go about this?

210
00:10:22,333 --> 00:10:23,791
Aren't the Amakusa
going to eat with us?

211
00:10:23,875 --> 00:10:25,666
I guess not. They said
something about being

212
00:10:25,750 --> 00:10:28,458
in training and needing to
observe a strict meal regimen.

213
00:10:28,541 --> 00:10:30,083
Toma!

214
00:10:30,166 --> 00:10:31,916
Go ahead. Please,
you should both eat

215
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:33,916
before your food gets cold.

216
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:35,666
Okay, then.

217
00:10:35,750 --> 00:10:38,125
[INDEX and KAMIJO]
Thank you for the food!

218
00:10:43,333 --> 00:10:44,500
[INDEX and KAMIJO] Yummy!

219
00:10:44,583 --> 00:10:46,833
Incredible! I never knew
pasta could be so good!

220
00:10:46,916 --> 00:10:48,666
[INDEX] I know! This is about
five hundred times better

221
00:10:48,750 --> 00:10:50,916
than what you usually
make at home, Toma!

222
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:52,708
[KAMIJO] Why do you
complain all the time?

223
00:10:52,791 --> 00:10:55,125
Oh, who cares? This
food is freaking amazing!

224
00:10:55,208 --> 00:10:57,000
[INDEX] So good! So good!

225
00:10:57,083 --> 00:10:58,791
So, you two...
since you're in the area,

226
00:10:58,875 --> 00:11:01,500
I'm guessing you'd like
to take a look at Venice?

227
00:11:01,583 --> 00:11:03,083
Yeah, we really want to.

228
00:11:03,166 --> 00:11:06,250
We can't get a hold of our tour
guide, though, so I don't know.

229
00:11:06,333 --> 00:11:07,458
But you have to see it.

230
00:11:07,541 --> 00:11:10,000
You'd be missing out
on something special.

231
00:11:10,083 --> 00:11:13,166
"The City of Water,"
"The Queen of the Adriatic."

232
00:11:13,250 --> 00:11:15,791
People have given many
different names to Venice.

233
00:11:15,875 --> 00:11:18,333
[ORSOLA] It's too
beautiful for just one.

234
00:11:18,416 --> 00:11:19,958
Well, I guess we'll
have to take a look.

235
00:11:20,041 --> 00:11:21,333
Right, Index?

236
00:11:21,416 --> 00:11:22,625
[INDEX] I couldn't care
less what we do just as long

237
00:11:22,708 --> 00:11:25,291
as I get to keep
eating like this!

238
00:11:26,166 --> 00:11:28,458
[KAMIJO]
What are you even saying?

239
00:11:34,583 --> 00:11:36,791
[KAMIJO] Uh! There we go.

240
00:11:40,458 --> 00:11:44,416
[vacuum humming]

241
00:11:47,875 --> 00:11:50,916
So, packing dishes
is next on the list.

242
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:53,166
Orsola! I need
to wrap the dishes.

243
00:11:53,250 --> 00:11:55,416
Where did you say
the newspaper is?

244
00:11:55,500 --> 00:11:58,583
[ORSOLA] It should be in one
of the rooms down the hall.

245
00:12:02,958 --> 00:12:04,375
Hm?

246
00:12:07,708 --> 00:12:09,958
[shower running]
[INDEX humming]

247
00:12:10,041 --> 00:12:11,250
[KAMIJO] That tune combined
with the sound of water

248
00:12:11,333 --> 00:12:12,250
can only mean...

249
00:12:12,333 --> 00:12:14,125
Wah! Look at me!

250
00:12:14,208 --> 00:12:15,875
There's dirt and
dust all over the place!

251
00:12:15,958 --> 00:12:17,375
I'm getting filthy!

252
00:12:17,458 --> 00:12:18,916
You're more than
welcome to take a shower

253
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:20,416
if you would like.

254
00:12:20,500 --> 00:12:22,875
You must be worn out from
your trip and all this packing.

255
00:12:22,958 --> 00:12:25,291
Back away, Toma!
I know what this is!

256
00:12:25,375 --> 00:12:28,375
The ol' bathroom trap! Whew!

257
00:12:28,458 --> 00:12:30,458
And to think I almost
fell for it, too!

258
00:12:30,541 --> 00:12:31,750
[ORSOLA humming]

259
00:12:31,833 --> 00:12:33,791
[KAMIJO] That same song again?

260
00:12:33,875 --> 00:12:35,375
Something's not right.

261
00:12:35,458 --> 00:12:37,583
What the hell is going on here?

262
00:12:37,666 --> 00:12:44,916
[INDEX and ORSOLA humming]

263
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:46,500
[KAMIJO] Surely there
wouldn't be two bathrooms

264
00:12:46,583 --> 00:12:48,000
across from each other.

265
00:12:48,083 --> 00:12:50,833
One of them will contain a
naked girl, and the other won't.

266
00:12:50,916 --> 00:12:54,541
Damn. What kind of
screwed-up choice is that?

267
00:12:54,625 --> 00:12:57,375
[KAMIJO] Right,
no, left. No, wait!

268
00:12:57,458 --> 00:12:59,250
I only hear the shower
coming from the left.

269
00:12:59,333 --> 00:13:01,500
So, the correct
answer is, the right!

270
00:13:01,583 --> 00:13:03,708
Yep! Got it! Here we go.

271
00:13:06,208 --> 00:13:09,208
[KAMIJO] As the reality began
to sink in, I had to wonder...

272
00:13:09,291 --> 00:13:11,458
Why didn't it occur to me
to just knock on the door

273
00:13:11,541 --> 00:13:14,291
and ask what was going
on before I walked in?

274
00:13:19,958 --> 00:13:23,083
[humming]

275
00:13:23,166 --> 00:13:25,000
Uh...

276
00:13:25,083 --> 00:13:30,250
♪

277
00:13:30,333 --> 00:13:32,916
[stuttering]

278
00:13:36,125 --> 00:13:37,625
[ORSOLA] Um, hello.

279
00:13:37,708 --> 00:13:40,625
Uh, I was sure that the
other door was the bathroom.

280
00:13:40,708 --> 00:13:42,333
I'm really sorry!

281
00:13:42,416 --> 00:13:43,875
[INDEX screams]

282
00:13:43,958 --> 00:13:46,875
What is this crazy contraption
that keeps blowing hot air?

283
00:13:46,958 --> 00:13:48,458
Ahhh!

284
00:13:56,875 --> 00:13:59,250
[KAMIJO] Wait! You mean,
there are two bathrooms?

285
00:13:59,333 --> 00:14:01,625
And they're right across
the hall from each other?

286
00:14:01,708 --> 00:14:04,958
[ORSOLA] Yes. One was
already here, of course.

287
00:14:05,041 --> 00:14:07,041
And, as for the other...
I had it installed

288
00:14:07,125 --> 00:14:09,291
for religious
use when I moved in.

289
00:14:09,375 --> 00:14:12,208
[ORSOLA] It functioned as
a separate area for baptisms.

290
00:14:12,291 --> 00:14:14,875
Now that I'm leaving
it is no longer needed.

291
00:14:14,958 --> 00:14:17,666
[KAMIJO] This is
ridiculous! I call foul!

292
00:14:17,750 --> 00:14:18,916
[INDEX] Toma.

293
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:20,375
What are you
doing poking around

294
00:14:20,458 --> 00:14:22,166
behind closed doors, anyway?

295
00:14:22,250 --> 00:14:24,458
And also, Toma, why
wasn't the first thing

296
00:14:24,541 --> 00:14:26,333
out of your mouth
an abject apology?

297
00:14:26,416 --> 00:14:28,750
Well, uh, you see,
Index, it's like this.

298
00:14:28,833 --> 00:14:31,083
I was just--I was looking
for some newspape--

299
00:14:31,166 --> 00:14:32,208
[INDEX growls]
[KAMIJO] Ahhh!

300
00:14:32,291 --> 00:14:34,291
[KAMIJO] Damn my luck!

301
00:14:35,375 --> 00:14:37,875
You two! You're so cute!

302
00:14:37,958 --> 00:14:41,125
[trunk running]

303
00:14:41,208 --> 00:14:42,708
[truck door closing]

304
00:14:42,791 --> 00:14:46,125
[ORSOLA] There we are. I believe
that is the last of the boxes.

305
00:14:51,708 --> 00:14:54,916
[ORSOLA] Thank you so much. I
really appreciate all your help.

306
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:56,291
I'm sorry to have kept you from

307
00:14:56,375 --> 00:14:58,791
enjoying your
vacation for so long.

308
00:14:58,875 --> 00:15:01,000
Well, what are you up
to for the next few days?

309
00:15:01,083 --> 00:15:02,416
You could always
come with us.

310
00:15:02,500 --> 00:15:04,041
We'll just be
seeing the sights.

311
00:15:04,125 --> 00:15:05,708
No, really I couldn't.

312
00:15:05,791 --> 00:15:08,791
Before long, you two will
be heading back to your hotel.

313
00:15:08,875 --> 00:15:11,000
And you don't want
me around for that.

314
00:15:11,083 --> 00:15:14,791
Like they say, two's company,
but three is a crowd.

315
00:15:14,875 --> 00:15:16,791
What? Why is three a crowd?

316
00:15:16,875 --> 00:15:18,083
That's not really
a topic we need to

317
00:15:18,166 --> 00:15:20,916
discuss any further, Index!

318
00:15:21,625 --> 00:15:23,916
And, anyway... I'd like
to take a little time to

319
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:27,125
go around Chioggia and
say goodbye to some people.

320
00:15:27,208 --> 00:15:30,166
I've lived in this city
for quite a while, you see.

321
00:15:32,041 --> 00:15:34,458
[ORSOLA] And, to be honest,
that's really the sort of thing

322
00:15:34,541 --> 00:15:36,458
I'd prefer to do on my own.

323
00:15:36,541 --> 00:15:40,458
I hate goodbyes, so I'm afraid
I may be a bit of a basket case.

324
00:15:40,541 --> 00:15:42,000
[KAMIJO] I see.

325
00:15:44,125 --> 00:15:48,125
[ORSOLA] Okay. I should be on
my way. I hope to see you again.

326
00:15:48,208 --> 00:15:49,833
If you have the chance,
you should definitely

327
00:15:49,916 --> 00:15:51,333
visit me in London sometime.

328
00:15:51,416 --> 00:15:53,333
[KAMIJO] Yeah.
You, too, if you're ever

329
00:15:53,416 --> 00:15:55,041
in our area again, I mean.

330
00:15:55,125 --> 00:15:56,500
[INDEX] You're going to
need to do a lot of cleaning

331
00:15:56,583 --> 00:15:59,000
before we can have guests, Toma.

332
00:16:00,041 --> 00:16:02,791
Hold on a second.
There's something--

333
00:16:02,875 --> 00:16:04,625
Get down, you guys!

334
00:16:04,708 --> 00:16:06,375
A-A-T-R.

335
00:16:09,416 --> 00:16:11,375
[gasps]

336
00:16:11,458 --> 00:16:12,291
[KAMIJO] Orsola!

337
00:16:12,375 --> 00:16:13,625
[ORSOLA] Oh, my!

338
00:16:13,708 --> 00:16:15,166
[KAMIJO] Index could
tell that something was up.

339
00:16:15,250 --> 00:16:16,500
And that means.

340
00:16:16,583 --> 00:16:17,500
It's magic!

341
00:16:17,583 --> 00:16:19,000
[ORSOLA] Magic?

342
00:16:20,458 --> 00:16:22,041
[groans]

343
00:16:24,041 --> 00:16:26,666
[KAMIJO] Where's it coming
from? Who's attacking us?

344
00:16:28,166 --> 00:16:31,166
[KAMIJO] Ah...!

345
00:16:31,250 --> 00:16:32,708
[INDEX] Toma!

346
00:16:33,958 --> 00:16:40,583
♪

347
00:16:40,666 --> 00:16:42,500
[INDEX] I-S-I-C-B-I.

348
00:16:43,208 --> 00:16:44,541
Ah...

349
00:16:51,416 --> 00:16:53,125
[KAMIJO grunts]

350
00:17:00,375 --> 00:17:03,833
[gasping for air]

351
00:17:03,916 --> 00:17:07,250
[breathing heavily]

352
00:17:07,333 --> 00:17:08,500
What about the sniper?

353
00:17:08,583 --> 00:17:11,500
No need to worry. It's
being dealt with already.

354
00:17:11,583 --> 00:17:13,833
What do you mean dealt
with? What did you do?

355
00:17:13,916 --> 00:17:16,416
[INDEX] If we're being attacked
so accurately from a distance,

356
00:17:16,500 --> 00:17:17,791
there must be
someone on the ground

357
00:17:17,875 --> 00:17:19,875
relaying the situation to him.

358
00:17:19,958 --> 00:17:21,791
And that means that no
matter where they're located,

359
00:17:21,875 --> 00:17:24,833
they must be taking in my
spell intercept, as well.

360
00:17:24,916 --> 00:17:26,541
[ASSASSIN groans]

361
00:17:26,916 --> 00:17:30,958
[ASSASSIN] Abbandoniamo
l'avanguardia! Torniamo subito!

362
00:17:31,041 --> 00:17:33,583
La ucciderò sulla nave!

363
00:17:33,666 --> 00:17:35,958
That must be the
sniper up there!

364
00:17:36,041 --> 00:17:38,041
[ALL gasp]

365
00:17:38,125 --> 00:17:45,625
♪

366
00:17:45,708 --> 00:17:48,375
Whoa! What's happening?

367
00:17:56,250 --> 00:18:06,208
♪

368
00:18:07,041 --> 00:18:08,541
[BOTH] Ah!

369
00:18:08,625 --> 00:18:09,833
[INDEX yelps]

370
00:18:09,916 --> 00:18:19,916
♪

371
00:18:32,916 --> 00:18:34,833
What? This is nuts!

372
00:18:34,916 --> 00:18:37,541
Something like this can't
just pop out of the canal!

373
00:18:37,625 --> 00:18:39,250
[ORSOLA struggling]

374
00:18:39,333 --> 00:18:41,541
Our best bet is probably
to get into the ship.

375
00:18:41,625 --> 00:18:43,750
[ORSOLA] Uh. Right.

376
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:51,333
What is this, glass?
No. I think it's ice.

377
00:18:51,416 --> 00:18:52,791
[BOTH gasp]

378
00:19:00,416 --> 00:19:03,750
[INDEX] Toma! Are you okay?
Where are you going?

379
00:19:03,833 --> 00:19:05,291
What do you think
a huge ship like this

380
00:19:05,375 --> 00:19:07,541
is doing sailing the canal?

381
00:19:08,833 --> 00:19:18,791
♪

382
00:19:30,250 --> 00:19:33,416
[ORSOLA] The canal! It appears
that we're heading out to sea.

383
00:19:33,500 --> 00:19:36,416
[KAMIJO] Yeah. I wonder
what the final destination is.

384
00:19:36,500 --> 00:19:37,458
[running footsteps]

385
00:19:37,541 --> 00:19:38,708
[BOTH gasp]
[running footsteps]

386
00:19:38,791 --> 00:19:42,500
[ASSASSIN 14B] Cerca!
Devono essere in dentro!

387
00:19:45,791 --> 00:19:48,000
[ORSOLA] What should we do?
It sounds like that man

388
00:19:48,083 --> 00:19:49,958
is deploying people
to search for us.

389
00:19:50,041 --> 00:19:52,333
[KAMIJO] I know,
but unfortunately...

390
00:19:52,416 --> 00:19:55,916
jumping overboard doesn't
look like a good option.

391
00:19:56,000 --> 00:19:59,416
I say we hide for now and
wait for a chance to escape.

392
00:20:08,458 --> 00:20:10,041
[INDEX] They're gone.

393
00:20:15,625 --> 00:20:19,166
Damn it! What in
the world is going on?

394
00:20:19,250 --> 00:20:23,791
[distant footsteps]

395
00:20:23,875 --> 00:20:25,416
We should go.

396
00:20:31,500 --> 00:20:33,958
[ORSOLA] I do hope
we aren't intruding.

397
00:20:35,458 --> 00:20:41,250
[distant footsteps]

398
00:20:43,833 --> 00:20:45,208
[sighs]

399
00:20:46,833 --> 00:20:48,208
[ORSOLA] I don't
understand why anyone

400
00:20:48,291 --> 00:20:49,625
would feel this
was necessary;

401
00:20:49,708 --> 00:20:52,541
sending an enormous ship
like this to attack me.

402
00:20:52,625 --> 00:20:54,875
Well, you know, the robes
those men were wearing

403
00:20:54,958 --> 00:20:56,583
do look a lot
like your habit.

404
00:20:56,666 --> 00:20:59,291
Yes. It is reasonable for
you to assume they are

405
00:20:59,375 --> 00:21:02,333
members of the Roman
Orthodox Church.

406
00:21:02,416 --> 00:21:03,750
And we know what that means.

407
00:21:03,833 --> 00:21:06,083
It's about the Book of the Law.

408
00:21:06,166 --> 00:21:07,541
I don't understand, though.

409
00:21:07,625 --> 00:21:09,416
That incident should
have been settled already.

410
00:21:09,500 --> 00:21:10,916
It's one of the
reasons I crossed over

411
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:12,541
to the English Puritan Church.

412
00:21:12,625 --> 00:21:15,500
[crash]

413
00:21:18,833 --> 00:21:28,791
♪

414
00:21:37,458 --> 00:21:40,125
[ORSOLA] It looks like the
ship we're on is far from alone.

415
00:21:40,208 --> 00:21:41,625
The enemy has
an entire fleet

416
00:21:41,708 --> 00:21:43,666
of magic vessels
at their disposal.

417
00:21:43,750 --> 00:21:45,083
I guess they couldn't
all deploy until

418
00:21:45,166 --> 00:21:47,125
we got to open water.

419
00:21:47,208 --> 00:21:49,958
[gasps] Index is back
there all alone--Wait!

420
00:21:50,041 --> 00:21:51,375
[beep-beep]

421
00:21:51,458 --> 00:21:53,458
Good thing I can
still use my cell phone.

422
00:21:53,541 --> 00:21:56,875
Aw, damn it. She didn't
bother to charge hers, though.

423
00:21:56,958 --> 00:21:59,500
[KAMIJO] I wonder how much
longer 'til the signal fades.

424
00:21:59,583 --> 00:22:01,958
[ORSOLA] I'm afraid
I have no idea.

425
00:22:03,791 --> 00:22:05,958
[KAMIJO] The door!

426
00:22:06,041 --> 00:22:08,166
Not good! Find
someplace to hide, Orsola!

427
00:22:08,250 --> 00:22:09,500
Yes, all right.

428
00:22:09,583 --> 00:22:11,333
Um, was there a particular
place you had in mind?

429
00:22:11,416 --> 00:22:13,000
Uh! Come here!

430
00:22:13,916 --> 00:22:15,791
Maybe it's just a draft
blowing the door op--

431
00:22:15,875 --> 00:22:17,125
Uh--

432
00:22:22,916 --> 00:22:24,583
[KAMIJO] Agnese?

433
00:22:26,208 --> 00:22:36,166
♪ [Ending Song] ♪

434
00:23:56,791 --> 00:23:59,333
[KAMIJO] An insane
ritual involving Agnese.

435
00:23:59,416 --> 00:24:02,291
A powerful secret weapon called
the Queen of the Adriatic.

436
00:24:02,375 --> 00:24:04,708
And now Tatemiya
and the Amakusa, too?

437
00:24:04,791 --> 00:24:06,625
Next time, "Queen's Fleet."

438
00:24:06,708 --> 00:24:09,875
When science and magic
cross paths, a story is born.

